            },
            "answer_text": "I can\u2019t say for sure, but if I had to guess, I would answer Pashto, or one of the Pamiri languages, owing to their close proximity to where Avestan is thought to have been spoken in north-eastern Iran. Yaghnobi might also be a candidate. Persian arose further south, and would likely be more distant to Avestan than any of these other guys. In linguistics, this sort of \u201cclosest\u201d questions are very hard to answer, since languages usually exist as dialect continua, and a single standardization might share some features with one part of the dialect continuum, and other features with another. Even western Iranic languages, like Persian or Kurdish, and especially the Caspian languages, might share significant features with Avestan. If I had to choose one at gunpoint, however, I\u2019d go with one of the Pamiri languages. ",
